abstract: Also this week, Kamala Harris releases a long-awaited plan, Elizabeth Warren wants to expand Social Security, and President Trump has a new Republican challenger.
snippet: Also this week, Kamala Harris releases a long-awaited plan, Elizabeth Warren wants to expand Social Security, and President Trump has a new Republican challenger.
lead_paragraph: A slimmed-down Democratic debate dominated this week’s campaign news — but there were other developments, too. Here’s our weekly catch-up on the 2020 election and the Democratic field.

abstract: They have staked out diverging political paths, but have mostly refrained from attacking each other. Now a more combative phase of the race seems inevitable.
snippet: They have staked out diverging political paths, but have mostly refrained from attacking each other. Now a more combative phase of the race seems inevitable.
lead_paragraph: If Joseph R. Biden Jr. and Elizabeth Warren are headed for a showdown, neither of them appears in a hurry to get there.

abstract: What a colleague says he missed the first time.
snippet: What a colleague says he missed the first time.
lead_paragraph: Early last year, Kevin Roose wrote an article about Andrew Yang’s entry into the 2020 presidential campaign. At the time, Yang’s candidacy was quixotic — he was not well known and had never held elected office — and Kevin’s tone was skeptical.

abstract: But Elizabeth Warren has revealed herself as a formidable adversary, and the president knows it.
snippet: But Elizabeth Warren has revealed herself as a formidable adversary, and the president knows it.
lead_paragraph: Julián Castro framed the debate almost perfectly in his opening statement: The 2020 election will be won or lost in a handful of states, starting with Michigan, Pennsylvania and Wisconsin, and maybe a few others like Arizona, where I live. So the question for Democrats remains what it has been all along: Who can beat President Trump in those states?

headline_main: So Far, Trump Is Winning the Democratic Debates

abstract: The Democratic National Committee has announced that the next debate will be held on Oct. 15, with a possible second night on Oct. 16.
snippet: The Democratic National Committee has announced that the next debate will be held on Oct. 15, with a possible second night on Oct. 16.
lead_paragraph: The New York Times and CNN will co-host the next Democratic debate near Columbus, Ohio, on Oct. 15, with the possibility of a second round one night later depending on how many candidates meet the qualifying criteria.

headline_main: Quiz Time: Keeping Up With the Democratic Debate

abstract: A serious discussion of Hispanic and Latin American issues was absent from the debate.
snippet: A serious discussion of Hispanic and Latin American issues was absent from the debate.
lead_paragraph: Perhaps the most notable feature of the Democratic presidential debate in Houston on Thursday was what the candidates did not say about Latin America, immigration, asylum and border security. This was in stark contrast to the detail with which they addressed health care, education, gun control and the war in Afghanistan. Their silence, half-truths or platitudes on these issues was surprising.

abstract: Ageism was on display in a debate where Democrats tried their hardest to dent Joe Biden’s enduring appeal.
snippet: Ageism was on display in a debate where Democrats tried their hardest to dent Joe Biden’s enduring appeal.
lead_paragraph: For months, they’ve been waiting for Joe Biden to collapse. Old Joe. Sputtering Joe. The Septuagenarian Slug. He’s That Seventies Show. The woke Democratic caucus waits for him to forget a name, or mistake his cellphone for the remote. Ditto the woke press. He mentioned “record player,” for God’s sake, answering a question about racism!
